post_text: We want to remind you that you can fill out a Free & Reduced Meals application at anytime. This program helps us feed our community, costs St. George MSU nothing, and if the percentage of our students who qualify for free or reduced meals exceeds the state average then out school could receive about $150,000 in additional state subsidy. If our percentage falls below the state average then we receive no state subsidy for economically disadvantaged students. You can fill out an application online at https://lunchapplication.com or access a paper copy at https://5il.co/i8la

post_text: The St. George School and Blueberry Cove are offering a before and after school program to help support parents in their return to work and to accommodate the new 9-3:30 school day. The before school program runs Mon-Fri from 7:30-8:30 with drop off at Blueberry Cove and a bus pick up to take students to school in the morning. The after school program meets Mon-Thurs 3:30-5:30 and Fri 12-3:30 at the St. George School. All health and safety protocols that apply during the school day will also apply at both of these programs. Families are still expected to screen for symptoms before dropping off in the morning. For more information on both programs as well as the link to register please click here: https://extension.umaine.edu/tanglewood/blueberry-cove-tenants-harbor-2/st-george-after-school-program/

School Breakfast, Lunch, and Snack

There is a new ordering procedure for breakfast and lunch this year:
-Link to order form: https://foodorder.stgeorgemsu.org/
-Orders will be placed for the full week and must be submitted by the
start of school on Friday for the following week.
-Copies of the monthly menu will be available on the school website,
at the above link, and paper copies will be made available to those
that need them.
-Families that do not have access to the digital order form can be
provided a paper copy each week to send in by Friday.

The September 2020 Menu can be found here: https://5il.co/kehr

Students will eat breakfast, lunch, and snack in their classrooms.

An email was sent out to St. George MSU families today with this information. If you have any questions, please contact the school directly (207) 372-6312.

Thank you!

St. George School's annual Math Camp will not be happening this August.

This cancellation breaks a chain of many successful summers where students at STG had the opportunity to practice skills and explore mathematically enriching problems; all while having fun and connecting with teachers and friends in the process.

We are confident that next summer will be a return to normal operating procedures and that we will once again be able to open our doors to summer learning.

If you have any questions or comments about math camp, please contact Adam Bullard at the school. a.bullard@stgeorgemsu.org

Town of St. George / Notice for Remote School Budget Public Hearing

Notice of Remote School Budget Public Hearing via Zoom on Tuesday, June 30, 2020 at 6:30p.m., as required by the Governor's June 3, 2020 Executive Order 56 and 20-A M.R.S. ¬ß¬ß 1486 & 1501, to discuss the proposed FY2021 School Budget. Please call the school (207.372.6312) or contact Business Manager Cassie Kilbride (c.kilbride@stgeorgemsu.org) or Superintendent Mike Felton (m.felton@stgeorgemsu.org) for information to join the public hearing using Zoom or by phone. More information about the proposed FY2021 School Budget is available on the school website (https://www.stgeorgemsu.org/o/st-george/browse/135116) and posted at various locations including the Town Office, Tenants Harbor General Store, and Tenants Harbor, Port Clyde, and Spruce Head post offices. If you have any questions about the budget or would like more information, please contact Cassie Kilbride or Mike Felton.

With the current state of things, we want to remind you that you can fill out a Free & Reduced Meals application at anytime.

This program helps us feed our community, costs St. George MSU nothing, and if the percentage of our students who qualify for free or reduced meals exceeds the state average then out school could receive about $150,000 in additional state subsidy. If our percentage falls below the state average then we receive no state subsidy for economically disadvantaged students.

You can fill out an application online at https://bit.ly/MSULunchApp or access a paper copy at https://bit.ly/STG-SY2020FRM.

Is it hard to fall asleep at night? Are your kids worried that they will catch the coronavirus? Are you or your kids worried about re-entering into the world? If these worries or any other are taking center stage for you or your kids right now, please consider coming to the parent support group this Thursday the 7th at 8 PM or next Monday the 11th at 3 PM. After checking in, our focus will be anxiety. We will try to explore questions such as What's the difference between stress and anxiety? How do we know when we or our children need more support? What are some concrete strategies to help reduce our children's and our own anxiety? Amy Hufnagel, the school-wide Behavioral Interventionist, will facilitate the meeting. We look forward to the conversation.

Complete this Google Form to receive an invitation: https://forms.gle/7fo6Nf8d4uZK8vyXA

post_text:
With the help of a volunteer filmmaker, the school is working to create a video featuring students, families, staff, and community members responding to the following prompts:

1. What is something you are grateful for during this time?

2. What does the St. George school-community mean to you?

You can respond with a recorded video or audio response, a drawing, or a written response. Please email responses to dragonstrong@stgeorgemsu.org.

With the help of the volunteer, we'll weave these messages together, along with images of St. George landmarks, into a short film. These stories will help keep us focused on the positive, spark some hope and joy over the weeks to come, and serve as another reminder that we're all in this together.

The Dragon WordArt is courtesy of 6th grader Isabella Lord.

post_text:
Thank you all - students, families, and staff - for your incredible work and relentless commitment to our kids, community, and one another. Check out this quote from a teacher describing her first day back with students after April break in the middle of a pandemic and extended school closure:

"Our kids are just amazing. They came back. We had phenomenal attendance today. I am sure it helped that it was a gloomy day, but I have had one of the longest -and most rewarding - days of my teaching career today. What a great school."

Nothing about this is easy and there have been - and will be - plenty of challenges and struggles along the way. However, it's important to recognize our community's resilience and celebrate those moments when - despite the obstacles - we find a way to make it work.

(Artwork and photo below courtesy of Madelyn MacCaffray)

In each lesson, parents will find a "read-aloud," activities to support phonological awareness and alphabet knowledge, and play-based extension activities that build vocabulary as well as social-emotional skills, comprehension, empathy, critical thinking, and problem-solving.

post_text:
Today, food service and transportation staff prepared and delivered 35 meals to students' houses. Students in grades K-8 began "remote" learning in earnest. I don't like the word "remote" because our teachers remain focused on fostering the relationships that are at the heart of student learning and growth.

When you keep the heart and relationship in "remote" learning, amazing things are possible. Ms. Ryan asked Ms. Albright's kindergarten class to draw a picture of something using their favorite color and then talk about their picture. Check out this video submitted by Elizabeth Hupper - that's high quality work! Keep the faith, keep smiling, and Go Dragons!!

Please visit the school website for the most up-to-date information on the COVID-19 virus and school closures:
https://www.stgeorgemsu.org/article/198029?org=st-george

Families can stop by tomorrow, Monday, 3/16, to pick up devices, books, and other student items.

Instructional and social work services will be delivered remotely beginning on Tuesday, 3/17.

Food service will continue. Families can sign up 1 week at a time to have breakfast/lunch meals delivered to their homes. Delivery will begin tomorrow. Sign up for meals here: https://foodorder.stgeorgemsu. The cost of meals for students will remain the same. Students who qualify for Free and Reduced Meals will continue to receive meals at no cost.

We are all in this together. Our greatest resource is ‚Äì and always has been ‚Äì our community. It is in times like these that you learn the true character of an individual, a community, and a people. Our school-community will rise to this challenge, take care of one another, and - above all else - care for our children. That is our mission and that‚Äôs what makes us Dragons.

post_text:
Minutes from the Monday, March 3, Early Childhood Education Working Group meeting are now available on the school website: https://www.stgeorgemsu.org/committees-and-working-groups

Over the past several years, this working group surveyed community members, visited Pre-K programs in the area and different parts of the state, met with Maine Department of Education officials, and did a lot of research and planning. At the January School Board meeting, representatives from the working group recommended that the Board consider starting a public Pre-K program at St. George school next school year.

Pre-K will be an important part of the FY21 school budget discussions this spring. Please join us at a budget workshop or School Board meeting and be part of this conversation. School Board and Budget Workshop dates can be found here: https://www.stgeorgemsu.org/o/st-george/events

post_text:
A BIG thank you to the St. George Alumni Association (SGAA) for their generous donations of $500 to the 8th Grade Class Trip and $500 to the St. George School Fund. SGAA officers President Austin Watts ('74), Vice President Jessie Thompson ('92), and Secretary Sandra Hall ('70) attended our February community meeting to present the checks and share information about the SGAA.

The SGAA is about fellowship and community service to the St. George School. If you attended St. George School for even one day, or are a current or former St. George School faculty or staff member, you are eligible to join. To learn more, follow this link (https://drive.google.com/file/d/19SQzlL-JOZ1ECBT8AZexE8btwNPdLPqZ/view) or contact the SGAA at StGeorgeMaineAlumni@gmail.com.

post_text:
St. George Middle Level students prepped lines and materials for kelp farming today. On a blustery cold day, they could see white caps in the harbor as they headed to the kelp shack. Students measured float rope and sink rope, collected mushroom anchors, poly balls and lobster buoys in preparation for sugar kelp farming. As we got back to the classroom everyone's noses were red and Georgie's glasses were fogged up!! (this post, photos and video were created by St. George Middle Level students)

See Video: https://youtu.be/DUA4Cdct70I

As we got back to the classroom everyone's noses were red and Georgie's glasses were fogged up!! (this post, photos and video were created by St. George Middle Level students)
